04749nam a22007215i 9780813570105DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2016043413  a97808135701057 a10.36019/97808135701052doi  a(DE-B1597)529191  a(OCoLC)992436757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aJV7037b.R64 2017 4aJV7037 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a304.8/7492231 aRodriguez, Robyn Magalit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Lady Liberty's Shadow :bThe Politics of Race and Immigration in New Jersey /cRobyn Magalit Rodriguez. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b9 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. The Politics of Race and Immigration in the "Garden State" -- t2. My Hometown: Immigration and Suburban Imaginaries -- t3. The New "Main Street"?: Ethnoburbs and the Complex Politics of Race -- t4. Being the Problem: Perspectives from Immigrant New Jerseyans -- t5. Fighting on the Home Front -- t6. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHome to Ellis Island, New Jersey has been the first stop for many immigrant groups for well over a century. Yet in this highly diverse state, some of the most anti-immigrant policies in the nation are being tested. American suburbs are home to increasing numbers of first and second-generation immigrants who may actually be bypassing the city to settle directly into the neighborhoods that their predecessors have already begun to plant roots in-a trajectory that leads to nativist ordinances and other forms of xenophobia. In Lady Liberty's Shadow examines popular white perceptions of danger represented by immigrants and their children, as well the specter that lurks at the edges of suburbs in the shape of black and Latino urban underclasses and the ever more nebulous hazard of (presumed-Islamic) terrorism that threatening to undermine "life as we know it." Robyn Magalit Rodriguez explores the impact of anti-immigrant municipal ordinances on a range of immigrant groups living in varied suburban communities, from undocumented Latinos in predominantly white suburbs to long-established Asian immigrants in "majority-minority" suburbs. The "American Dream" that suburban life is supposed to represent is shown to rest on a racialized, segregated social order meant to be enjoyed only by whites. Although it is a case study of New Jersey, In Lady Liberty's Shadow offers crucial insights that can shed fresh light on the national immigration debate. For more information, go to: https://www.facebook.com/inlibertysshadow  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aImmigrantszNew JerseyxHistory. 0aImmigrantszNew Jersey. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aellis island, new jersey, nj, immigrant, immigration, city, neighborhood, suburb, xenophobia, foreign, foreigners, black, Latino, terrorism, islamophobia, minority, american, american dream, anti-immigration, undocumented, illegal, alien.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813570105zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813570105423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813570105.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA